GLOSSARY

ACTIONS

  • Basic Attacks: Basic attacks are the heart of the system. Each turn players may take a basic attack action for free. They are also able to modify these attacks using the abilities outlined below. Basic attacks can come in various forms and can be creative in the emote phase. You cannot replicate any ability through Basic Attack.
    A BASIC ATTACK HITS FOR TWO (2) DAMAGE.


  • Talents: Effects specific to each calling individually, that provide a variety of different passive abilities.



  • Active Abilities: Active abilities are abilities that can be used only during a players turn and modify attacks, defenses or have some other effect.


  • Reactive Abilities: Reactive abilities are based on other actions, and can only be triggered by another ability or certain defined circumstances. Each ability will define its own proc.

    >>>> When resolving multiple reactive abilities follow the "Last to be Cast-- First to Resolve" theory. This means the last reactive ability in a chain will be the first to work when resolving begins.

  • Passive Abilities: Passive abilities are background abilities that increase stats for free.

    TARGETS

  • Enemy/Unfriendly - Any player or NPC on an opposing team


  • Friendly - Any player or NPC, including yourself, on your team.

    TIME

  • Round - A full rotation of the initiative order. All characters’ attack actions and resolutions.

  • Turn - A single “Declare, Emote, Roll, Defender Emote” phase.

    MISC

  • Ward - A type of proactive damage reduction. If a character has any wards, they are spent FIRST before applying damage to a character. Wards are used in the order of Temporary Wards, Wards applied by knights, and then all other wards.





COMBAT RULES

  • No First Turn KO Rule: In the Gladiator System, no participant may be knocked below 1 HP in the first round of fighting. Their HP will be set to 1 HP until the second round begins. Abilities that spend HP are not affected by this rule and can bring you down to 0 HP.

  • Rule of Three: No Morddus System ability can have more than 3 points spent on it per turn by one player. A friendly target cannot receive more than 3 of the same buff from friendlies or same debuff from unfriendlies a turn.

  • To Hit Cap: No bonuses to hit chance may stack to a point that a player is rolling with MORE than +5 to hit or LESS than -5 to hit.

  • Damage Reduction: Any ability that prevents damage as it is occurring is considered damage reduction.

  • Heal: Any ability that returns HP to any character.

  • Knocked Out: A character is considered 'knocked out' when their HP is reduced to 0.

  • No Null Expenditure: You cannot spend zero points to activate an ability


Stats

Participation Roll Bonuses - Participation roll bonuses are applied to both attack and defense rolls and are awarded through participation in 2 Dueling / Gladiator events each season. They are NOT awarded through training events, only through arena dueling. They may be applied in both Adventure RP AND Gladiator RP.
SEASON PARTICIPATION: +1
SEASON WINNER: +2

Participation mod carries into the next season, but you lose it if you don't participate for a whole season. Season winner mod carries into the next season, but downgrades to participation mod if you don't win the following season.
HP / AP / MP

Hit points for all characters = 5

AP = Action Points
MP = Magic Points

By Path:

Warriors - 5 AP/3 MP
Rogues - 4 AP/4 MP
Mages - 3 AP/5 MP

Characters gain their Path stats as soon as they declare a Calling, even if they are unable to use any abilities.

Paragons gain a +1 to any single resource of their choosing. May be moved while quicksheets are open

Apostles & Path Heads receive their +1 bonus for participation whether they participate or not. It does NOT stack with actual participation bonus, but if they champ they can get the +2.
Subdivisions of the System
The Morddus System is subdivided into two distinct systems for use either in Orders/Adventure RP or Paths/Gladiator RP. Each has some small but distinct differences to cadence and flow of combat.


Orders Adventures System - This is used for any adventure within the guild guided by a DM. It is most often used for Orders events, but may also be used for Paladin quests, Curate quests, random encounters designed by members, or any other event where guild members are invited to PvE against made up NPC baddies.

Paths Gladiator System - This system is used for player vs player dueling. Dueling is the primary means by which our characters train for martial proficiency. It is often called 'The Arena', 'The Sands', PvP, Gladiator system, Paths system etc.


See below for more details:


The Adventure System is used for Orders events and general PvE type role play. It does not apply to the Arena/Gladiator Events. For more information on Gladiator rules, keep scrolling down...


The phases of the adventure system proceed at the discretion of the DM. Players will not move from one phase to the next without instruction to do so.

Turn Sequence

1. Start of the turn- Players Declare
2. Players roll
3. Players emote success
4. DM emotes the NPC


1. Start of turn- Players Declare
The DM can use pre-generated Minions and Bosses from the forums or design their own for the role play. The DM decides who goes first. No initiative is ever rolled in the adventure system. The DM will tell you when to DECLARE, which is when you will type in your basic attack and skill usage.

A ‘Declare’ looks similar to following: Basic Attack at ZOMBIE (5 hp/ 5 ap/ 3 mp)
You would announce your ‘Basic attack’ and your target whether its a person’s name or an NPC, (then following this any skill names you would like to activate), and then end the string with your personal updated stats of (HP/AP/MP) once per round. Include here if you have a league participation bonus.

Examples:

Basic Attack @ Dale// (Resolute Smite [active]: 1 MP = +2 dam --Using 2 MP-- (5HP/ 5AP/1MP) +1 League Bonus

Basic Attack @ Vampire Lord// (Distraction Expert [active]: per 1 MP = +2 to Defense roll) --Using 1 MP-- (3HP/3AP/4MP) +2 League Champion Bonus

2. Players roll
The DM guides the phases in party chat. Roll 1d10 and include any roll bonuses. The DM will tell you if you succeed or fail to hit. If you are told to succeed, that means your roll was equal to or higher than the Minion's or Boss's defense threshold. In this case, you would successfully deal 2 damage on a basic attack.

To Roll in Discord please use the following examples:

General Roll: ?roll 1d10
Example 1: ?roll 1d10+1
Example 2: ?roll 1d10-2


3. Players emote success (or failure)
Once all players have rolled, they can emote a successful attack if they have been told to by the DM. A failure to hit may still be emoted at the DM's discretion.


4.DM emotes the NPC
Once all players have emoted the DM will emote the NPC's attack. In the NPC attack emote or in group chat, the DM targets specific players. Those players will roll a d10 for defense, and will be told whether they succeed or fail by the DM. If a player is wounded by a Minion or Boss, they can emote as soon as they receive the damage. The round ends when the DM asks for ‘Declares.’
Some examples of a Minion group and a boss would be the following:


Undead Skeletons (Minions)
HP: 3
Number of attacks: 3
Attack dice: 1d10-2
Damage per attack: 1
Defense threshold: 3
Action abilities: N/A
Magic abilities: N/A


Undead Giant (Boss)
HP: 20
Number of attacks: 4
Attack dice: 1d10+2
Damage per attack: 2
Defense threshold: 6
Action abilities: You may forgo making a regular attack and make a stun attack as you would a normal attack. If this attack his the target suffers no damage but cannot attack for 2 rounds.
Magic abilities:You may forgo one of you attacks to spawn an undead skeleton with 1HP, 1 attack, an attack dice of 1d10-2, damage of 1 and defense threshold of 3.







WIN CONDITIONS

  • Knockout: If a character is reduced to 0 HP they are considered knocked down or out. In Company matches all three opponents must be knocked out for this win condition.

  • Time Limit: Combat will have a set time limit. This will usually be 30 minutes for Solo and 2v2 or 55 minutes for Company, but can change depending on participation. Any willful attempt to delay actions in order to run the clock out will be ruled as such and that player or team will forfeit the match.

  • In Case of Draw: If time has run out, the winner will be the individual or team with most players standing and THEN who has spent the least of the recorded resources (Combined HP AP and MP). If both of these numbers are the same, it goes to sudden death.

  • Sudden Death: Once combat goes into sudden death, initiative order is rerolled and the first person or team to score a hit is the winner.

  • Season Champions: Wins will be tracked through the season. The two teams with the MOST wins will face off against one another in the Championship Match. If there is a tie among teams with the most wins, resources used throughout the season will pick the finalists. Prior to the Championship match, the Companies will vie for ranking in the arena (3rd, 4th, 5th, 6th place etc). These matches will be organized based on the above criteria as well.



Turn Sequence


  1. Start of the turn- Any effects that take effect at the beginning of a turn take place during this phase.
  2. Attacker declares- The expenditure of resources occurs, insert the application of an active ability to a basic attack.
  3. Attacker emotes
  4. Attacker rolls
  5. Defender rolls- Immediately after the defender rolls, all weapon effects are assigned simultaneously, then all basic attack and active ability effects as assigned simultaneously, then reactive abilities that trigger resolve.
  6. Defender emotes


  • Start of turn:
    At the very start of the combat and only in the first turn, each player will roll an unmodified 1d10. The player with the highest roll becomes the attacker this turn. The lower roll becomes the defender.

  • Attacker declares:
    Before they can roll or emote, the attacker needs to declare their intentions in party chat. They must state if they are using only a Basic Attack, what passives they are using, and what Active Abilities (if any) they are using, as well as how many MP or AP they are spending.

  • Attacker emotes
    The attacker will perform an emote where he makes an attack against the defender, leaving it slightly open as to whether they have actually succeeded or failed. In doing so they can use 1 active ability. They must state what ability they are using (preferably in the declaration stage), how much they spend, and the effect it has before they roll.

  • Attacker and Defender roll
    The attacker and defender will then both roll 1d10 and add the relevant modifiers below. If the Attacker rolls higher than the defender, he causes, by default, 2 hit points of damage, unless an Ability changes that number. If the defender rolls equal to or higher than the attacker, he successfully defends and no damage is caused. During this phase if a player has a forge weapon, and rolled their number the forge weapon ability activates.

  • Defender emotes
    The defender emotes his success or failure at defending from the attack. The defender then becomes the attacker and the turn begins again. Repeat in this order until one player wins.


If a player makes a roll out of sequence, that roll will not count for that action.
Following the correct turn sequence is vital for clarity of action and scorekeeping purposes.

If making a defense and your character is the next in the sequence of turns, you may combine your defense and attack emotes into one outside the normal turn sequence.

Special Abilities

In order to set the Paths and Callings apart from one another, Special Abilities will be utilized to create diversity and extra flavor to combat. These abilities will be gained through RP and progression within the guild systems.

They will be gated as follows:
ABILITY PROGRESSION

Disciples use base roll system. No Special Abilities granted.

Sentinels gain access to one Calling ability slot. Must be a Calling ability. In addition to gaining their calling's Talent after declaring.

Paladins gain access to one Background ability slot. Must be a Background ability



Curates gain access to one Curate ability slot. Must be a Curate ability.

Paragons gain a +1 to any single resource of their choice. May be changed while quicksheets are open.



Each Calling has access to the following abilities:
